<subSubSection lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1734,2012]" lastBlockId="26.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1915,1940]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Description.</emphasis>
Body length: 
<quantity box="[515,621,1915,1939]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.34" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="13.4">13.4 mm</quantity>
; setae only black, but mixed golden and black on legs; antennomeres uniformly black, III more than 
<number box="[500,535,1950,1975]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times as long as IV; pronotum with an evident fore transverse depression; elytra with two fore spots, one middle wide spot, forming almost a transverse stripe, one subapical wide and transverse spot, almost forming a stripe, and a very narrow apical margin (
<figureCitation box="[902,986,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1020,1042]" captionTargetBox="[225,1356,417,994]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[218,1369,411,998]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 13. Mylabris (M.) desertica Bologna: A. elytral pattern; B. mesosternum. Scale bar = 1 mm. (from Bologna &amp; Turco, 2007)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286154/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[958,986,152,176]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
A); mesosternum as in 
<figureCitation box="[1260,1343,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1020,1042]" captionTargetBox="[225,1356,417,994]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[218,1369,411,998]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 13. Mylabris (M.) desertica Bologna: A. elytral pattern; B. mesosternum. Scale bar = 1 mm. (from Bologna &amp; Turco, 2007)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286154/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[1314,1343,152,176]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
B. Male unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,151,357]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,440,223,248]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Taxonomic remarks</emphasis>
. This species is highly distinct because of the elytral black pattern, which includes a transverse incomplete fascia in apical third; a similar black spot is present only in 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[1067,1188,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mylabris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="madoni">
<emphasis box="[1067,1188,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">M. madoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1242,1367,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[1242,1363,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mylabris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olivieri">M. olivieri</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
being easily distinguished from it by the antennal and setae colour (see below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
